  "descriptions": [
    {
      "descrType": "Overview",
      "description": "The Pratt &amp; Whitney F135 is an afterburning turbofan jet engine developed for the Lockheed Martin F-35 Lightning II multirole fighter. Designed specifically for the F-35&#x27;s supersonic operations and high maneuverability requirements, the F135 powers all variants of the F-35 (F-35A, F-35B, and F-35C). The engine features a single-stage high-pressure ratio compressor, large bypass ratio for fuel efficiency, and integrated health management systems.",
      "shortDescription": "Afterburning turbofan engine for the F-35 Lightning II fighter aircraft.",
      "classification": "U"
    },
    {
      "descrType": "Design",
      "description": "The F135 employs a low-bypass-ratio turbofan architecture with three low-pressure compressor stages and a single high-pressure compressor stage. The engine incorporates advanced cooling techniques for the high-pressure turbine and uses titanium and nickel-based superalloy materials for enhanced temperature and stress resistance. A full authority digital engine control (FADEC) system manages all engine operations automatically, optimizing performance across the flight envelope. The engine operates at a turbine inlet temperature of approximately 1,700 K.",
      "shortDescription": "Advanced turbofan with FADEC, titanium/superalloy construction, and high turbine inlet temperature.",
      "classification": "U"
    }
  ],
